Clinical use of blood:
Unnecessary transfusions and unsafe transfusion practices expose patients to the risk of serious adverse transfusion reactions and transfusion-transmissible infections. Unnecessary transfusions also reduce the availability of blood products for patients who are in need.
WHO recommends the development of systems, such as hospital transfusion committees and haemovigilance, to monitor and improve the safety of transfusion processes. In this regard:
- 129 countries have national guidelines on the appropriate clinical use of blood: 34 countries in the African region (76% of reporting countries in the region), 20 in the Americas (65%), 15 in the Eastern Mediterranean (88%), 34 in Europe (81%), 9 in the South East Asia (82%), and 17in the Western Pacific (77%);
- transfusion committees are present in 40% of the hospitals performing transfusions: 43% in hospitals in high-income countries, 37% in upper-middle-income countries, 46% in lower-middle-income countries and 37% in low-income countries;
- systems for reporting adverse transfusion events are present in 68% of the hospitals performing transfusions: 88% in hospitals in high-income countries, 41% in upper-middle-income countries, 62% in lower-middle-income countries and 39% in low-income countries; and
- 88 countries (representing 52% of the 168 responding countries) reported having a haemovigilance system.
